technology, commerce, and maritime culture – transcend historical periods, Basil Germond frames contemporary seapower as a combination of components, including traditional naval power, post-modern conceptions of collective and civilian seapower, and the neo-modern phenomena of maritime territorialization and the naval arms race.By giving seapower a new conceptual definition, Seapower in the Post-modern World offers key analytical tools for understanding the stability of the global maritime order and seapower’s contribution to global leadership more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aInternational relations. 0aSea-power. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  a.  aAlfred T. Mahan.  aAthens.  aChina.  aEngland.  aGreat Discoveries.  aHanseatic League.  aJulian Corbett.  aMiddle Ages.  aPax Americana.  aPax Britannica.  aRome.  aRussia.  aSea.  aaircraft carrier.  acivilian power.  acolonization.  aculture.  adominance.  ageopolitics.  aglobal supply chain.  agovernance.  ahegemony.  ahistory.  aimperialism.  ainternational order.  amarine environment.  amodernity.  anation-state.  anaval forces.  anaval power.  anavy.  aocean.  aships.  asoft power.  asolidaristic society.  astrategy.  asubmarine.  aworld order.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228020899?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228020899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228020899/original  a978-3-11-140848-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles